{{About|the RMSP's 1888 screw steamer Atrato|the RMSP's earlier paddle steamer|RMS Atrato (1853)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Use British English|date=February 2018}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= StateLibQld 1 133537 Atrato (ship).jpg |Ship caption= ''Atrato'' }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country= United Kingdom |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|government}} |Ship name= ''Atrato'' |Ship namesake= [[Atrato River]] in [[Colombia]] |Ship owner=*[[File:Royal Mail Lines House Flag.svg|15px]] [[Royal Mail Steam Packet Company|RMSP Co]] (1888–1912) *Viking Cruising Co (1912–14) |Ship operator= {{flagicon|UK|naval}} [[Royal Navy]] (1914–15) |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= |Ship builder= [[Robert Napier and Sons]], [[Govan]] |Ship yard number= 410 |Ship laid down= |Ship launched= 22 September 1888 |Ship christened= |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned= |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship route= [[Port of Southampton|Southampton]] – Brazil – [[Uruguay]] – Argentina (1889), Southampton – [[Caribbean]] (1889–1912) |Ship registry=*{{flagicon|UK|civil}} (1888–1914) *{{flagicon|UK|naval}} (1914–15) |Ship identification= UK [[official number]] 95512 |Ship renamed=*''Viking'' in 1912 *HMS ''Viknor'' in 1914 |Ship reclassified= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship fate=Sunk 13 January 1915 |Ship status= |Ship homeport= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship type=*[[ocean liner]] (1889–1912) *[[cruise ship]] (1912–14) *[[Armed merchantman#Armed merchant cruisers|armed merchant cruiser]] (1914–15) |Ship tonnage= {{GRT|5347}}, {{NRT|3069}} |Ship length=*{{convert|400|ft|abbr=on}} [[Length between perpendiculars|p/p]] *{{convert|421.2|ft|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|o/a]] |Ship beam={{convert|50|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship depth={{convert|33|ft|4|in|abbr=on}} |Ship draught={{convert|25|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship sail plan= 3-masted [[schooner]] |Shi