'''RMS ''Atrato''''' was a UK [[steamship]] that was built in 1888 as a [[Royal Mail Ship]] and [[ocean liner]] for the [[Royal Mail Steam Packet Company]]. In 1912 she was sold and became the [[cruise ship]] '''''The Viking'''''. Toward the end of 1914 she was requisitioned and converted into the [[Armed merchantman#Armed merchant cruisers|armed merchant cruiser]] '''HMS ''Viknor'''''. She sank in 1915 with all hands, a total of 295 [[Royal Navy]] officers and men.
==Building== In the 1880s RMSP introduced a series of larger new ships to improve its scheduled services between [[Port of Southampton|Southampton]], [[South America]] and the [[Caribbean]]. The first was the {{GRT|4572}} {{RMS|Orinoco|1886|2}}, built by [[Caird and Company]] and {{liy|1886}}. She was RMSP's first new ship to have a hull of steel rather than iron.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=87}} After her success RMSP ordered two more ships to an improved and enlarged version of the design from [[Robert Napier and Sons]] of [[Govan]]. ''Atrato'' was {{liy|1888}}, followed by {{RMS|Magdalena|1889|2}} {{liy|1889}}. Before these were completed RMSP ordered two more from Napier: the slightly larger {{RMS|Thames|1889|2}} in 1889 and {{RMS|Clyde|1890|2}} {{liy|1890}}.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=87}}
''Orinoco'' had only a small amount of deck housing and was the last square-rigged sail-steamer to be built for RMSP. The Napier ships were more modern, each with a full superstructure deck and rigged as a three-masted schooner.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=88}} The smaller sail plan was based on the increasing economy and reliability of their engines.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=87}}
''Atrato''{{'}}s boilers had a working pressure of 150 [[Pounds per square inch|lb<sub>f</sub>/in<sup>2</sup>]].{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=89}} She had eight of them, supplying steam to one three-cylinder [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple expansion steam engine]] that drove a single [[Propeller|screw]]. This gave her a top speed of {{convert|16|kn|km/h}} on [[Sea trial|trials]]{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=87}} and a service speed of {{convert|14|kn|km/h}}.<ref name=Clydesite>{{cite web |url= http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=504 |last1=Cameron |first1=Stuart |last2=Biddulph |first2=Bruce |title=RMS Atrato |work=Clydebuilt database |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>
The ship's passenger capacity included 176 in first class state rooms and nearly 400 emigrants in steerage class. Her cargo capacity was 2,524 tons and her coal bunkers 1,109 tons. She had {{convert|6000|cuft}} of refrigerated storage space for provisions,{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=87}} using a dry-air refrigeration system with a discharge rate of {{convert|10000|cuft}} of air per hour.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=89}} She had tanks for {{convert|20000|impgal|l|abbr=off}} of fresh water.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=88}}
''Atrato'' was launched on 22 September 1888,{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=87}} named after the [[Atrato River]] in [[Colombia]]. RMSP named all of its ships after rivers; many of them with Hispanic names to reflect its trade with [[Latin America]].
==Civilian service== ''Atrato''{{'}}s [[maiden voyage]] began from Southampton on 17 January 1889. As well as her passengers, mails and a full cargo she carried in her strong room £120,000 in [[Sovereign (British coin)|sovereigns]], jewellery worth £2,000 and [[Bullion|silver bars]] worth £400. She called at Carril, [[Port of Vigo|Vigo]] and [[Lisbon]], and then crossed the Atlantic to South America. There she worked her way down the east coast, calling at [[Pernambuco]], [[Maceió]], [[Bahia]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Santos, São Paulo|Santos]], [[Port of Montevideo|Montevideo]] and [[Port of Buenos Aires|Buenos Aires]].{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=84}} ''Magdalena'', ''Thames'' and ''Clyde'' joined the same South American route over the next 18 months,{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=91}} but after her maiden voyage ''Atrato'' was switched to join ''Orinoco'' on RMSP's Caribbean route.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=84}} All five sisters had long and successful careers.
The five ships' furnaces suffered from heat damage, so in 1891 they were lined with [[zinc]].{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=89}} In 1899 [[Day, Summers and Company]] of Southampton raised the boats on ''Atrato'', ''Magdalena'', ''Thames'' and ''Clyde'' "to a boat deck clear of the promenade" at a cost of more than £5,000. In 1903 ''Atrato'', ''Magdalena'' and ''Clyde'' were fitted with bronze propellers costing another £5,000. In May 1905 RMSP ordered insulation and refrigeration to be fitted to part of their cargo space to enable ''Orinoco'' and ''Atrato'' to carry fresh fruit.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=90}}
In October 1912 the Viking Cruising Company of London bought ''Atrato'' and renamed her ''The Viking''. She became a cruise ship, touring the waters of [[northern Europe]].{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=90}}
==Naval service and loss== [[File:SS Bergensfjord in 1927.jpg|thumb|The Norwegian liner {{SS|Bergensfjord||2}}, which ''Viknor'' detained in 1915]] When the UK entered the [[World War I|First World War]] in 1914 the [[Admiralty]] requisitioned her, had her re-fitted as an armed merchant cruiser and commissioned her as HMS ''Viknor''.<ref name=Clydesite/> She was placed under the command of [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Commander]] EO Ballantyne<ref name=Wrecksite>{{cite web |url= http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?11823 |last=Allen |first=Tony |title=HMS Viknor [+1915] |publisher=Wrecksite.eu |date=22 September 1913 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> with a [[Ship's company|complement]] of 22 officers and 273 [[Naval rating|ratings]] and assigned to the 10th Cruiser Squadron.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=90}}
On 28 December 1914 ''Viknor'' went on patrol from the [[River Tyne]], and on 1 January she joined "B" patrol off the north coast of Scotland.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=90}} The patrol was ordered to find and stop the neutral [[Norwegian America Line]] ship {{SS|Bergensfjord||2}}, which the UK Government believed was carrying a suspected German spy. ''Viknor'' found ''Bergensfjord'', detained her and escorted her to [[Kirkwall]] in [[Orkney]]. There the suspect and a number of other prisoners were transferred to ''Viknor'', which then left for [[Port of Liverpool|Liverpool]].{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=90}}
''Viknor'' never reached her destination. On 13 January 1915 she sank with all hands in heavy seas off [[Tory Island]], [[County Donegal]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D04EFDB1538E633A25755C2A9679C946496D6CF |title=British Auxiliary Lost |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=26 January 1915 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> She sent no [[distress signal]].<ref name=Wrecksite/> Some wreckage and many corpses washed ashore on the northern coast of Ireland.{{sfn|Nicol|2001b|p=90}}
It is thought she struck a German [[naval mine]], possibly one of those laid by the German {{sclass-|Bremen|cruiser}} {{SMS|Berlin}}.<ref name=Shipspotting>{{cite web |url= http://www.shipspotting.com/gallery/photo.php?lid=1541452 |title=The Viking |publisher=Shipspotting |year=2012 |accessdate=2 October 2014}} – includes photo of the ship in [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company|Palmers]] Dock, [[Hebburn]]</ref> Her wreck was found<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.maritimequest.com/liners/02_pages/a/atrato_1888_page_1.htm |title=Atrato (1888) |work=Maritime Quest |publisher=Michael W Pocock |accessdate=2 October 2014}} – photographs of ''Atrato'' and her wreck</ref> in 2006,<ref name=Shipspotting/> and in 2011 a [[Scuba diving|scuba diver]] placed a [[White Ensign]] on it in memory of her complement.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://vimeo.com/24974583 |title=HMS Viknor |publisher=[[Vimeo]] |accessdate=2 October 2014}} – placing of a White Ensign on the wreck by scuba diver Stewart Andrews</ref>
